<Author>Gridfather
<Content>Nice Hotel, Friendly Staff, Undesirable Location A conference my wife attended over a weekend in March '08 was located at this hotel. The renovation construction referenced by other reviewers must be complete. Our room was updated and clean with new furniture and a flat screen TV. The bathroom was also clean. The bed was WONDERFUL. The staff was extremely helpful and willing to please; they exceeded my expectations. The swimming pool is open. Taxi cabs are available onsite 24 hours a day.Fridays and Saturdays are chaotic as cruise ship passengers are checking in and out prior to cruising.I ate one meal at the sports bar attached to the lobby. Prices have a hotel premium but are not outlandish. The menu was small but varied. I overheard other guests complaining about the cost of the breakfast buffet ($20) in the restaurant. Many cruise ship passengers had vouchers for breakfast, thus the buffet.The only reason to stay at this hotel is if a conference were located at the hotel, at the adjacent Knight Convention Center, or prior to departing on a cruise. The hotel is nice but the location undesirable. I would have much rather stayed in South Beach which has restaurants, beaches, and architecture. My impression is that the renaissance of Miami Beach over the past 20 years has come at the expense of Downtown, at least for the traveler. The hotel overlooks the Miami River, but who comes to Miami for the view of a river? There is a river promenade which is blocked by chain link fencing down to a 2-3 block length and is essentially abandoned due to a vacant lot on one end and condo construction at the bridge.The neighborhood surrounding the hotel is a concrete jungle and not pedestrian friendly. Many sidewalks are closed due to the number of condo towers in various phases of construction, including halted construction. The I-95 entrance/exit ramp adjacent to the hotel is, at times, treacherous to cross as a pedestrian. Bayfront Park, the Bayside entertainment district and the Mary Brickell (rhymes with pickle) Village are all within walking distance, past vacant storefronts and unfinished construction. Did I mention the area is dirty? There is a lot of litter and a general grittiness. The Metromover, the free downtown loop monorail, is convenient but in need of attention. The stations are dirty, some have graffiti. Each of the stations we visited after dark had an onsite security guard on the platform, which was needed. I never felt safety was an issue but I felt I needed to be more aware of my surroundings than in other major cities. If one were not an adventurous traveler, I could see where the surrounding area would be intimidating. My stay at the hotel was pleasant but the neighborhood needs improvement. 
