<Author>OffTheBeatenPath
<Content>Dull, unexceptional, with a frown on its face If you're used to the Motel 6, this hotel will be seem like luxury. However, if you're used to any level of service or comfort in hotels, the Hyatt will seem shabby. (Don't get me wrong, Motel 6 is great but doesn't cost $179/night at the corporate rate -- and there are hotels in the same price bracket as the Hyatt that are much better.)My main complaint was service. For example: My flight, already scheduled to arrive late in the evening, was delayed, so I arrived at the hotel at 11:45 p.m. after not having had anything to eat since breakfast. The woman at registration checked me in efficiently, but was clearly unenthused about doing so (not a single smile or pleasant tone of voice). When I asked if I could get any food, she told me room service was open until midnight but I'd better order at the bar. The bartender growled at me that the kitchen was closed; when I pointed out that I'd been informed it was open for another 15 minutes, only then did she get me a menu and let me order. Again, no smiles, clearly no joy in her job. (It's not the best job in the world, likely, but still, they are paid to be service-oriented.) Every time I dealt with anyone in the hotel over the next three days, they were borderline surly -- not a single smile ever, even when smiled at.When I got to my room, housekeeping had left the balcony door open and the lights on, so the room was humid and crawling with bugs. There was only one toiletry in the room: lotion. No soap, shampoo or conditioner. I called the desk and asked for some; an hour later none had arrived. I called again -- at 1:15 a.m. -- and only then did they bother to inform me they had none at the desk, housekeeping was closed, and they couldn't send anything up. (An hour+ of sleep lost.)The bed in the room was decent -- clearly upgraded recently to compete with other chains -- and the decor was fine, not exceptional but not offensive. On the other hand, the bathroom grout was full of mildew and the whole bathroom smelled of mold.Another plus: The fitness room was good -- not a ton of machines (basically two of everything), but what they had was new, with TV screens built in.The bar was pretty depressing -- low rent 80s decor with the clientele to match. It's named Currents -- which of course means it's the least current place you can imagine. (nice neon changing pastel colors behind the sign...very late 80s)If you have to stay in downtown Miami and you want a modicum of style for the same price, go to the Intercontinental. If you want to pay too much for a Holiday Inn room, go to the Hyatt. 
